  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "Finding a suitable dataset for training a deep learning model for patent or prior art search can be a bit challenging, but there are several places where you can find patent datasets, both free and paid. Here\u2019s a list of potential sources:\n\n### Free Datasets:\n1. **The Lens**: The Lens offers a comprehensive database of patents and scholarly works that you can access for free. They allow users to build search queries and extract relevant data for research purposes.\n   - Website: [The Lens](https://www.lens.org/)\n\n2. **United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO)**: The USPTO provides free access to patent data, including full-text patents, images, and XML datasets. They also offer bulk downloads of patent data.\n   - Website: [USPTO Patent Data](https://www.uspto.gov/developer/)\n\n3. **European Patent Office (EPO) \u2013 Espacenet**: Espacenet provides access to millions of patent documents and allows users to perform searches. They also offer bulk data for researchers, although it may require a formal request.\n   - Website: [Espacenet](https://www.espacenet.com/)\n\n4. **Google Patents**: Google Patents provides access to a large database of patents and allows users to search and view documents. Though not as accessible for raw data extraction, the interface is user-friendly.\n   - Website: [Google Patents](https://patents.google.com/)\n\n5. **PATENTSCOPE**: Offered by the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO), PATENTSCOPE provides access to international patent applications and full-text patent documents.\n   - Website: [WIPO PATENTSCOPE](https://patentscope.wipo.int/)\n\n### Paid Datasets:\n1. **Clarivate Analytics (Derwent Innovations Index)**: A subscription-based service that provides access to an extensive database of patents, with advanced search capabilities.\n   - Website: [Clarivate](https://clarivate.com/)\n\n2. **LexisNexis PatentSight**: A commercial patent analytics tool that offers insights into patent portfolios and trends, which may be useful for your training data.\n   - Website: [LexisNexis PatentSight](https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/westlaw)\n\n3. **Questel**: Questel offers patent search tools and databases, which can be valuable for comprehensive patent analysis and prior art searches.\n   - Website: [Questel](https://www.questel.com/)\n\n### Other Considerations:\n- **Wikipedia and Open-Source Projects**: Sometimes open-source projects or research papers might share custom datasets, especially if they pertain to natural language processing in the patent domain.\n- **Kaggle**: A data science community that often hosts competitions and datasets. You might find datasets related to patents.\n  - Website: [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/)\n\n### Tips:\n- Consider combining datasets from multiple sources to enrich your training data.\n- Make sure to read the terms of use for each dataset, especially for commercial applications.\n- Look for datasets with annotations or classifications relevant to prior art searches if available.\n\nBy leveraging these resources, you should be able to find datasets suitable for training a deep learning model focused on patent or prior art searches.",
